    "caption": "The garden's tiny spotted superhero.",
    "shortDescription": "Ladybugs are beetles, and they're beloved by gardeners because they eat aphids — the sap-sucking pests that wreck plants. A single ladybug can eat hundreds of aphids in a day. Their bright red-and-black spots warn birds that they taste awful. Fun fact: When threatened, a ladybug leaks a little drop of bitter yellow liquid from its leg joints — a trick called reflex bleeding."
